consonants). If something was only IDed to genus, then XXX was
filled in for the last three letters of the species code (ex.
SMLXXX for Smilax spp.). For some mixes of species a common-form
name was used, such as &quot;grass&quot; for any mix of unidentified
combination of upland grass species, &quot;herb&quot; for unknown herbaceous
species, or &quot;salthay&quot; for a mix in various proportions of Spartina
patens and Distichilis spicata.</para></section></section></description></methodStep></methods><project scope="document"><title>Parramore Permanent Plot Project</title><personnel scope="document"><individualName><givenName>John</givenName><surName>Porter</surName></individualName><address scope="document"><deliveryPoint>UVA, Department of Environmental Sciences, 291 McCormick Road, P.O. Box 400123</deliveryPoint><city>Charlottesville</city><administrativeArea>VA</administrativeArea><postalCode>22903-4123</postalCode><country>USA</country></address><phone phonetype="voice">434-924-8999</phone><phone phonetype="facsimile">434-982-2137</phone><electronicMailAddress>jhp7e@virginia.edu</electronicMailAddress><role>originator</role></personnel><abstract><section><para>First 3-5 year resurvey of permanent monitoring plots using
